CREATED:20260403T201633Z
DESCRIPTION:Masterclass with Tamara Williams and Moving Spirits\, Tuesday\
 , 4/7/26 4:30-5:55 PM RAC Studio 224. \n\nEmbodied Dialogues V: Memory Wo
 rk and Body Landscaping - Ancestral Practices in African Brazilian Dance 
 residency is a collaboration between Duke University Professor of Dance\,
  Ava LaVonne Vinesett\, and UNC-Charlotte College of Arts + Architecture'
 s Associate Professor of Dance\, Tamara Williams.  Now\, in our fifth yea
 r\, our intergenerational group of artists and scholar-practitioners cent
 ers Black memory as an embodied\, ethical\, and collective practice. This
  residency understands memory not as static history\, but as labor carrie
 d in the body and shaped by land\, ritual\, and lived experience. Body la
 ndscaping names the ways movement practices reconfigure how memory is hel
 d\, transmitted\, and returned-across African Brazilian dance traditions 
 and landscapes animated by ancestral power\, defiant joy\, and the pleasu
 re of return.\n\nFull schedule:\n\n- Tuesday\, 4/7/26 4:30-5:55 PM RAC St
 udio 224\, Masterclass with Tamara Williams and Moving Spirits guests\n\n
 - Tuesday\, 4/7/26 6:00-8:00 PM RAC Studio 202\, Music/Song/Memory Work T
 amara Williams and Moving Spirits guests\n \n- Wednesday\, 4/8/26 6:15-7:
 45 PM RAC Studio 224\, Masterclass with Tamara Willams and Moving Spirits
  guests\n\nPlease go to the following site for information on parking.  W
 e are not distributing parking passes: https://parking.duke.edu/visitor-p
 arking/blue-spot-hourly-parking/
DURATION:PT1H30M
DTSTAMP:20260403T203233Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260407T163000
LAST-MODIFIED:20260403T203233Z
