CREATED:20260220T170210Z
DESCRIPTION:The Juan E. Méndez Book Award for Human Rights in Latin Americ
 a honors the leadership and legacy of Juan E. Méndez\, a champion of just
 ice who has devoted his life to the defense of human rights. This is the 
 seventeenth year of this prestigious award. The award is supported by the
  Duke Human Rights Center@the Franklin Humanities Institute\, Duke's Cent
 er for Latin American and Caribbean Studies\, and the Human Rights Archiv
 e at the Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library.\n\nThe 2026 winner of
  the Méndez Book Award is "A Flower Traveled in My Blood: The Incredible 
 True Story of the Grandmothers Who Fought to Find a Stolen Generation of 
 Children\," by Haley Cohen Gilliland. In the book\, Gilliland documents h
 ow the Argentine Grandmothers of the Plaza de Mayo set out to find their 
 grandchildren\, abducted by the military junta in the 1970s and 80s. With
  determination and creativity\, the abuelas marched\, confronted the auth
 orities\, allied with local and international human rights groups\, and p
 ioneered the use of genetic testing to find their loved ones. This is des
 pite the intense grief of losing their adult children\, "disappeared" by 
 the security forces.\n\nReception starts at 5:00pm. Cohen Gilliland's rea
 ding starts at 5:15pm. Books will be available for purchase and signing.
DURATION:PT1H30M
DTSTAMP:20260323T201816Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260407T170000
LAST-MODIFIED:20260323T201816Z
